          <avActivityHighlights>A lot of snow fell in the past few hours. Towards its surface, the snowpack is unstable.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>Over a wide area 40 to 60 cm of snow, and even more in some localities, fell yesterday above approximately 2000 m. &lt;br/&gt; The new snow of yesterday can be released easily or naturally especially on steep sunny slopes. &lt;br/&gt; Above approximately 2200 m: The covering of new snow is weak. Avalanches can be released in near-surface layers and reach large size in particular on steep east, southeast and south facing slopes. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In particular below approximately 2100 m and on very steep slopes gliding avalanches and moist snow slides are possible as the moisture increases.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>Over a wide area new snow and wind slabs are lying on a hard crust. &lt;br/&gt; The meteorological conditions will bring about a weakening of the near-surface layers as the day progresses in particular on east, south and southwest facing slopes. The sleet will give rise to extreme moistening of the snowpack below approximately 2100 m.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>The new snow of the last few days remains for the foreseeable future prone to triggering.</tendencyComment>
